\section{Summary}
%================================================

\begin{frame}{Mathematical Summary}
The logic of Gibbs sampling is:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item start from a target distribution \(\pi\),
    \item identify tractable conditionals \(\pi(x_i\mid x_{-i})\),
    \item define a Markov chain by local conditional updates,
    \item prove invariance using conditional factorization,
    \item obtain convergence under ergodicity assumptions.
\end{enumerate}

Gibbs sampling is a special rejection-free case of Metropolis--Hastings.
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Practical Summary}
We also added:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Metropolis comparison,
    \item autocorrelation and effective sample size,
    \item mixing-time intuition,
    \item blocked Gibbs strategies,
    \item Gibbs sampling in Boltzmann machines,
    \item Gibbs sampling in Bayesian networks.
\end{itemize}

So Gibbs sampling is both:
\begin{itemize}
    \item a rigorous MCMC method,
    \item and a unifying algorithmic idea across physics, statistics, and machine learning.
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Final Take-Home Message}
Gibbs sampling works because exact local conditional sampling reconstructs the full global distribution.

\medskip

Its strengths:
\begin{itemize}
    \item mathematical clarity,
    \item exact conditional updates,
    \item wide applicability.
\end{itemize}

Its weaknesses:
\begin{itemize}
    \item can mix slowly,
    \item suffers in strongly correlated or multimodal systems,
    \item may require blocking or other improvements in hard problems.
\end{itemize}

This makes Gibbs sampling one of the foundational bridges between equilibrium physics and probabilistic inference.
\end{frame}

